00:16:25.179 --> 00:16:34.299
of this. So, big takeaways. When you are thinking about deploying content, the top three things

00:16:34.299 --> 00:16:40.200
to really optimize for are accessibility, reproducibility, and security, right? If you're

00:16:40.200 --> 00:16:45.659
hitting these three keys, you're probably increasing value with what you're doing as

00:16:45.659 --> 00:16:50.780
opposed to just adding sophistication. While you're doing that, R markdown, shiny, plumber,

00:16:50.780 --> 00:16:59.900
and pins are good friends of yours. And, of course, may the force be with you. Thanks,

00:16:59.900 --> 00:17:01.900
everybody.

00:17:01.900 --> 00:17:14.099
So, I failed to mention at the top of things here, but if you have questions, we're going

00:17:14.099 --> 00:17:19.579
to continue using Slido as we did in the keynote. So we're in Grand Ballroom B, so if you have

00:17:19.579 --> 00:17:24.579
a question, go to the same Slido page, select Grand Ballroom B, and you can enter your questions

00:17:24.579 --> 00:17:28.619
there or vote on questions that are already asked there. So I'm going to ask Alex some

00:17:28.619 --> 00:17:33.979
questions here since we have a couple minutes. Maybe this was covered in the last half of

00:17:33.979 --> 00:17:38.540
your presentation, but do you want to readdress how pins is different from a well-organized

00:17:38.540 --> 00:17:41.260
shared file system with correct ACLs?

00:17:41.260 --> 00:17:46.819
Yeah, that's a great question. To be honest, under the hood, it's not that different, right?

00:17:46.819 --> 00:17:50.939
You have the same kind of control and access controls. The main difference is that it's

00:17:50.939 --> 00:17:56.300
a very R-centric answer, and so you can, from within R, address those objects without having

00:17:56.300 --> 00:18:00.140
to go through the hassle of figuring out how your shared file system works, finding

00:18:00.140 --> 00:18:04.099
things and that sort of thing. So from an IT perspective, maybe not that different,

00:18:04.099 --> 00:18:08.219
but from the perspective of an R developer, it's a very different development experience.

00:18:08.219 --> 00:18:09.219
It's much more straightforward.

00:18:09.219 --> 00:18:16.579
Yeah. This next one we get a lot, so I'm happy to ask it here. What's the benefit of using

00:18:16.579 --> 00:18:21.579
a plumber API for saving the object to S3 and then calling it with a Shiny app?

00:18:21.579 --> 00:18:26.420
Oh, that's a great question. I love that question. There are a couple benefits. One

00:18:26.420 --> 00:18:30.900
is that you can, the biggest benefit to me, and this happens in several different ways,

00:18:30.900 --> 00:18:36.619
is that it decouples the logic of serving the model from the logic of displaying whatever

00:18:36.619 --> 00:18:40.300
you're displaying or doing something else with it. So you decouple those things, and

00:18:40.300 --> 00:18:42.780
that makes your life easier. It makes your life easier in a couple ways. One of them

00:18:42.780 --> 00:18:46.660
is purely from a code perspective. It makes it easier to write the code because you write

00:18:46.660 --> 00:18:50.380
your plumber API to serve the model, you write your Shiny app or whatever it is to consume

00:18:50.380 --> 00:18:54.140
the model, and you get to sort of separate those concerns, which is really nice. The

00:18:54.140 --> 00:18:58.060
other piece from a performance perspective, you can test those two things independently.

00:18:58.060 --> 00:19:01.579
You can test the plumber API with, say, the load test package, which I think some people

00:19:01.579 --> 00:19:05.500
might be talking about next. And then you can test the Shiny app separately. You can

00:19:05.500 --> 00:19:11.780
decouple both the coding and the performance issues between the API and the app, which

00:19:11.780 --> 00:19:17.780
is great. Excellent. Okay. Next, is there a limit to the amount of data you should be

00:19:17.780 --> 00:19:23.500
using with pins? It depends on which board you're using. Some of those boards do have

00:19:23.500 --> 00:19:28.699
limits to how much you can save. You know, my suggestion would be that if you're saving

00:19:28.699 --> 00:19:32.979
more than a gigabyte's worth of data, there's probably a better solution for what you're

00:19:32.979 --> 00:19:39.660
doing. And that's totally a rule of thumb, not a real thing. But just in general, if

00:19:39.660 --> 00:19:43.920
you're finding yourself doing more than that, you're probably saving an object that's bigger

00:19:43.920 --> 00:19:48.800
than pins really is designed for. One thing that can be helpful is if you're saving model

00:19:48.800 --> 00:19:52.599
objects, often the model objects package up a lot of stuff with it that you don't necessarily

00:19:52.599 --> 00:19:57.319
want, like the training data. And that could make your model really big and sort of inflate

00:19:57.319 --> 00:20:03.599
the size. There is a package called butcher, like, you know, a person who makes meat cuts,

00:20:03.599 --> 00:20:07.079
that you can use to sort of chop out some of the stuff in your model object you don't

00:20:07.079 --> 00:20:10.760
want and just save, like, actually the model. So if you're saving models, that can be a

00:20:10.760 --> 00:20:11.760
useful thing to do.

00:20:11.760 --> 00:20:17.479
Cool. Do one more here. I like this one as well. Is there a reason your import and model

00:20:17.479 --> 00:20:21.800
training code is in R Markdown files instead of plain R scripts?

00:20:21.800 --> 00:20:24.479
Yes, that's a great question. I love it when things that I put in the presentation and

00:20:24.479 --> 00:20:29.680
then took out because I didn't have time come back in questions. Yeah, so I really love

00:20:29.680 --> 00:20:34.160
R Markdown for two main reasons. One is that it encourages literate programming that is

00:20:34.160 --> 00:20:38.800
interspersing code and prose, right? Because you have just, like, a place to write prose.

00:20:38.800 --> 00:20:42.640
It doesn't even have to be comments. You just write it, and it's great. The other reason

00:20:42.640 --> 00:20:45.959
that you have a record of what you did. So when you come back later and something has

00:20:45.959 --> 00:20:50.680
gone awry with your model, you have output there with the code of what actually happened,

00:20:50.680 --> 00:20:54.839
unlike if it's just an R script and then whatever happened was totally ephemeral and it's gone

00:20:54.839 --> 00:20:55.839
forever.

00:20:55.839 --> 00:20:59.839
Well, everyone, please join me in thanking Alex again.

00:20:59.839 --> 00:21:00.839
Thanks, everybody.

00:21:00.839 --> 00:21:00.839


